  "text": "The Kafka consumer fetch request processing chain in apache/kafka involves multiple Java source files that work together to retrieve and parse records. The flow begins with the Fetcher class (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/Fetcher.java), which is the main consumer fetcher implementation. When a consumer calls poll(), the Fetcher.sendFetches() method is invoked to prepare and send fetch requests to brokers.\n\nThe request building phase starts in AbstractFetch.prepareFetchRequests() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AbstractFetch.java:412), which determines which partitions need to be fetched and creates a map of nodes to FetchSessionHandler.FetchRequestData objects. This method examines the subscription state and determines which partitions are fetchable and don't have buffered data. Each partition is added to a FetchSessionHandler.Builder, which manages incremental fetch sessions.\n\nAbstractFetch.createFetchRequest() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AbstractFetch.java:301) then builds the actual FetchRequest using FetchRequest.Builder.forConsumer() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/requests/FetchRequest.java:166). The FetchRequest.Builder allows configuration of isolation level, max bytes, fetch size, and other parameters. The request is sent through the network using the Fetcher's ConsumerNetworkClient.\n\nWhen the broker responds with a FetchResponse (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/requests/FetchResponse.java), the response handler AbstractFetch.handleFetchSuccess() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AbstractFetch.java:150) processes it. This method extracts the FetchResponseData.PartitionData from the response and creates a CompletedFetch object (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CompletedFetch.java:59) for each partition in the response. Each CompletedFetch object is added to the FetchBuffer, which maintains a queue of completed fetches ready for consumption.\n\nThe record parsing phase begins when FetchCollector.collectFetch() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/FetchCollector.java:92) is called to convert buffered CompletedFetch objects into ConsumerRecords. For each CompletedFetch that needs to be processed, FetchCollector.fetchRecords() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/FetchCollector.java:150) calls CompletedFetch.fetchRecords() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CompletedFetch.java:252), which iterates through the raw records in the response.\n\nEach individual Record from the RecordBatch is processed through CompletedFetch.parseRecord() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CompletedFetch.java:307), which deserializes the key and value bytes using the configured Deserializers and creates a ConsumerRecord object. This parseRecord method handles key/value deserialization, extracts headers, manages timestamps, and handles isolation level logic (e.g., filtering aborted transactions for READ_COMMITTED isolation).\n\nThe parsed ConsumerRecord objects are collected into a Fetch object (which is a container for ConsumerRecords grouped by partition) that is ultimately aggregated into a ConsumerRecords collection (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/ConsumerRecords.java:34) and returned to the user.\n\nThe entire chain integrates FetchSessionHandler (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/FetchSessionHandler.java) to manage incremental fetch sessions, FetchBuffer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/FetchBuffer.java) to buffer completed fetches, and FetchMetricsAggregator to track metrics for bytes read and records parsed per partition."
}

